<h3>Face Recognition Resources on the Internet</h3>
<ul>
  <li>The <a href="http://www.face-rec.org/">Face Recognition homepage</a>
(very comprehensive set of pointers to research, data sets, etc)</li>
  <ul>
    <li><a href="http://www.face-rec.org/interesting-papers/">Research
papers</a> on face recognition<br>
    </li>
  </ul>
  <ul>
    <li><a href="http://www.face-rec.org/databases/">Databases
of face images</a> for research</li>
  </ul>
  <li>Information about <a
 href="http://faculty.washington.edu/chudler/java/faces.html">how our
brain recognizes faces</a> (from Washington University)<br>
  </li>
  <li>Mitsibushi Electric Research Laboratory <a
 href="http://www.merl.com/projects/gender/">project
on gender classification from face images</a></li>
  <li>Research at Colorado State on <a
 href="http://www.cs.colostate.edu/evalfacerec/">evaluation of face
recognition algorithms</a></li>
    <li><a href="http://www.frvt.org">Official tests of face recognition
systems</a> by the US government<br>
  </li>
  <li>A magazine article on <a
 href="http://www.eetimes.com/story/OEG19990405S0017">recognizing
facial expressions</a>. <br>
  </li>
  <li><a href="http://www.epic.org/privacy/facerecognition/">Privacy
issues</a>
related to face recognition (includes an extensive set of references)<br>
  </li>
  <li>A <a
 href="http://www.theregister.co.uk/content/archive/21916.html">skeptical
look</a> at face recognition</li>
</ul>
